ACADEMICIANS have challenged journalists to sharpen their skills so as to be competent in writing news that impact the country's development positively. The call was made recently during the joint think tank symposium that was organized by the Research on Poverty Alleviation (REPOA), Media Space and the US Embassy in Tanzania The event was presided by the capacity building training on impact, investigative and digital journalism to 20 journalists from various media houses in Mwanza. The symposium was focusing on  capacity building to journalists in examining the 60 years of media sector evolution in Tanzania (since independence), together with celebrating 25 years of REPOA operation since its inception. The Lecturer from University of Dar es Saalam School of Journalism and Mass Communication (SJMC), Dr Darius Mukiza commented that journalists should develop a critical eye, which will enable enlisting and add the light to issues, such as significance of the Royal Tour, through analysis so as to build the country's economy. “Journalists should publish more news story in order to enrich themselves with required skills in the everlasting changing field of journalism. This also will help on building individual journalist career recognition as self-defence in the competitive arena of employment,” he said. On his part, Tanzania Media Women Association’s (TAMWA) Information and Technology Officer, Mr Godwin Assenga said that the current trend in the media industry needs journalists to cultivate digital skills and application of those skills in digital platform, including the good use of social media. He said that digital  age allows massive publication of news for development and needs active journalists to counteract citizen journalism, so as to make sure the disseminated news on social media are of accuracy. The Nukta Africa Executive Officer, Mr Nazulack Dawsen, commented that the quality of media contents in Tanzania still have low use of data in reporting different socio-economic and political issues, calling on regular capacity building to capacitate the journalists.